@flexiarg orchestration/recorded-handoff
@title The Recorded Handoff — dispatch as a modeled object
@keywords handoff, orchestration, traceability, bell, mission, commit-trailer, review-gate, multi-agent
@audience multi-agent coordinators, mission authors, futon3c implementers
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [social/scope-bounded-handoff futon-theory/agent-contract futon-theory/proof-path mission-coherence/logic-model-before-code]

! conclusion: A coding handoff to a worker agent is not a message; it is a MODELED OBJECT with a lifecycle, recorded in the mission document that owns it: spec + acceptance bar + gates at dispatch, job-id on send, bell-back summary + commit shas on return, review verdict at the gate — and the worker's commits carry a Mission: trailer so the output tape (code/v05/commit→mission) attributes the work mechanically. The record makes the handoff auditable by the same scope instruments that audit everything else in the mission.

  + context: One operator orchestrates several coding agents (Claude-family
    reviewers/authors, Codex workers) under a subscription-runtime rebalance:
    substantial coding flows to workers, the orchestrator holds review.
    The dispatch volume is high (nine handoffs on 2026-06-11 alone) and the
    mission documents are typed, scope-detected objects.

  + IF:
    Handoffs are working well as messages — bells with goal, files,
    acceptance bar, gates, and a bell-back contract (the CLAUDE.md
    coding-handoff protocol, adopted 2026-06-03 to rebalance runtime).

  + HOWEVER:
    A handoff that lives only in the message channel is invisible to the
    mission it serves. Six months later the mission doc says a thing was
    built but not who built it, under what spec, against what acceptance
    bar, or which commits answered it. The dispatch→result chain exists
    only in job stores and chat scrollback — exactly the
    logging-without-propagating trap. And the audit instruments
    (scope detector, Skolem binding audit, the commit→mission output tape)
    cannot see objects that were never written down.

  + THEN:
    1. The mission INSTANTIATE section carries one record per handoff:
       spec summary, acceptance one-liner, worker, Job: <job-id> stamped at
       dispatch, Bell-back: filled on return (summary + commit shas +
       review verdict).
    2. The bell instructs the worker to include a "Mission: <mission-id>"
       trailer in its commit messages, so commit→mission attribution is
       declared, not inferred (provenance "trailer" beats
       "session-heuristic" in the transducer's edge ranking).
    3. The bell-back is reviewed at a real gate (author ≠ reviewer; re-run
       the stated gates; findings fixed by the reviewer, not re-belled) and
       the verdict enters the record.
    4. Records use a stable textual form so the scope detector can bind
       them (candidate binder: handoff, with job-id and bell-back state as
       ends — a chip that turns from amber to green when the bell-back
       lands).

  + BECAUSE:
    The pattern earns its place twice. From the COORDINATION standpoint it
    extends social/scope-bounded-handoff: that pattern constrains what a
    worker may touch; this one makes the whole exchange a first-class
    object in the artifact that owns it. From the MODELING standpoint
    (the deeper reason): a recorded handoff joins the mission's scope tree,
    the Skolem audit's binding flow, and the commit→mission output tape —
    the orchestration layer stops being exhaust and becomes part of the
    system's model of its own work. What is recorded can be audited;
    what is attributed can be queried; what is typed can be rendered.

    + EVIDENCE:
      M-smart-emacs-cursor §6 (futon3c, 2026-06-11) — first full instance,
      conducted by voice:
      - H1 (completion-bubble subscriber → codex-1): spoken directive →
        record typed into the mission by the agent cursor → bell
        invoke-1781178866343-683-497c41fe (typed bell, kind request) →
        bell-back ~25 min with commit bfdb482 — "Mission:
        M-smart-emacs-cursor" trailer VERIFIED in the commit object, the
        first mission-attributed commit in the stack's history → review
        gate (check-parens OK, ert 4/4) → verdict typed back into the
        record. Chain complete, every link on disk.
      - H2 (watcher scope lane → codex-2): same form, job
        invoke-1781178866664-684-b47bd48f, in flight at time of writing.
      - Origin: runtime rebalancing experiment (Codex gets runtime when the
        Claude subscription is the binding constraint), CLAUDE.md protocol
        2026-06-03; ~9 dispatches on 2026-06-11 under it.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    1. Mint the handoff binder (15th) in mission_scope_detect.py once the
       record form stabilizes; verdict-style coloring per bell-back state.
    2. Join records to the transducer lane: a recorded job-id plus a
       trailer-attributed commit should reconcile mechanically; flag
       records whose commits never arrive (the undischarged-handoff smell).
    3. Backfill records for the 2026-06-11 dispatch wave where the missions
       they served still lack them.
